INSERT INTO contract_templates (contract_type, jurisdiction, version, title, preamble, recitals, clauses, signature_block, placeholders, is_active, metadata) VALUES (
  'independent_contractor',
  'uk',
  1,
  'Consultancy Agreement (United Kingdom)',
  'This Consultancy Agreement (the "Agreement") is entered into as of {{effective_date}} (the "Effective Date"), by and between {{party_a_company}}, a company registered in England and Wales with company number {{party_a_company_number}} and registered address at {{party_a_address}} ("Client"), and {{party_b_company}}, with address at {{party_b_address}} ("Consultant"). Client and Consultant may be referred to individually as a "Party" and collectively as the "Parties".',
  'WHEREAS, Client desires to engage Consultant to perform certain consultancy services described in this Agreement; and
WHEREAS, Consultant represents that Consultant has the expertise, resources, and ability to perform such services as an independent contractor and not as an employee or worker of Client;
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises contained herein, the Parties agree as follows:',
  '[{"id":"services","title":"1. SERVICES","content":"1.1 Services. Consultant shall perform the services described in {{services_description}} (the \"Services\") in a professional manner, consistent with generally accepted industry standards and using reasonable skill and care.\n\n1.2 Deliverables; Schedule. Any deliverables, milestones, deadlines, and acceptance criteria shall be as specified in {{services_description}} or as otherwise agreed in writing by the Parties.\n\n1.3 Place and Manner of Performance. Consultant will determine the method, details, and means of performing the Services; provided that Consultant shall reasonably cooperate with Client''s operational and security policies when accessing Client''s facilities, systems, or personnel. Client does not have the right to direct or control how Consultant performs the Services, only the outcome.\n\n1.4 Changes. Client may request changes to the scope of Services. Any material change affecting scope, timeline, or fees must be agreed to in writing by both Parties.\n\n1.5 No Authority. Consultant has no authority to bind Client, incur obligations on Client''s behalf, or make representations as an agent of Client unless expressly authorised in writing.","type":"standard","order":1},{"id":"compensation","title":"2. FEES; INVOICING; EXPENSES; VAT","content":"2.1 Fees. As full consideration for the Services, Client shall pay Consultant as follows: (a) a total fee of {{payment_amount}} and/or (b) a day rate or hourly rate of {{hourly_rate}}, as applicable to the Services described in {{services_description}}.\n\n2.2 Invoicing and Payment. Consultant shall invoice Client in accordance with the invoicing schedule stated in {{services_description}}. Unless otherwise stated, Client shall pay undisputed amounts within 30 days of receipt of a valid invoice.\n\n2.3 Expenses. Unless expressly authorised in advance in writing by Client, Consultant is responsible for all expenses incurred in performing the Services. Any pre-approved reimbursable expenses must be supported by reasonable documentation.\n\n2.4 VAT. All fees are exclusive of Value Added Tax (VAT). If VAT is applicable, Consultant shall add VAT at the prevailing rate to invoices, and Client shall pay such VAT. Consultant shall provide a valid VAT invoice where applicable.\n\n2.5 Taxes and National Insurance. Consultant is solely responsible for all taxes, National Insurance contributions, and other governmental charges arising from fees paid under this Agreement. Client will not withhold PAYE (Pay As You Earn) or make employer National Insurance contributions for Consultant, except as may be required under the off-payroll working rules (IR35).\n\n2.6 No Employee Benefits. Consultant acknowledges that Consultant is not eligible for Client-provided employee benefits, including holiday pay, sick pay, pension contributions, maternity/paternity pay, or other employment benefits.","type":"standard","order":2},{"id":"consultant_status_ir35","title":"3. CONSULTANT STATUS; IR35 OFF-PAYROLL WORKING RULES","content":"3.1 Independent Contractor. Consultant is engaged as an independent contractor and not as an employee or worker of Client within the meaning of the Employment Rights Act 1996, the Agency Workers Regulations 2010, or any other applicable legislation. Consultant shall control the manner and means of performing the Services, subject only to the requirements of this Agreement.\n\n3.2 No Employment Relationship. Nothing in this Agreement shall be construed to create an employment relationship or worker relationship. Consultant shall not represent that Consultant is an employee or worker of Client.\n\n3.3 IR35 Off-Payroll Working Rules. The Parties intend that the engagement under this Agreement falls outside the scope of the off-payroll working rules (commonly known as \"IR35\") as set out in Chapter 10 of Part 2 of the Income Tax (Earnings and Pensions) Act 2003. The Parties have considered the nature of this engagement, including by reference to HMRC''s Check Employment Status for Tax (CEST) tool, and believe that if the Services were provided directly by Consultant (or an individual representing Consultant) to Client, Consultant would not be regarded as an employee or office holder of Client for income tax purposes.\n\n3.4 Status Determination Statement (SDS). If Client is a \"medium or large\" entity as defined by the off-payroll working rules and is required to make a Status Determination Statement:\n(a) Client shall use reasonable care in making the determination;\n(b) Client shall provide Consultant with the SDS and reasons for the determination;\n(c) The Parties shall cooperate in good faith to ensure the correct status is determined;\n(d) Consultant may dispute the determination through Client''s disagreement process;\n(e) If the engagement is determined to be within IR35, Client shall comply with its obligations as the fee-payer or deemed employer.\n\n3.5 Right of Substitution. Consultant has the unrestricted right to provide a suitably qualified and experienced substitute to perform the Services, subject only to: (a) prior notification to Client; and (b) the substitute agreeing to Client''s reasonable confidentiality requirements. Consultant shall remain responsible for the substitute''s performance and compliance with this Agreement. Client shall not unreasonably refuse a proposed substitute. The exercise of this right is at Consultant''s discretion and Consultant may also delegate work to assistants as appropriate.\n\n3.6 No Mutuality of Obligation (MOO). There is no mutuality of obligation between the Parties beyond the specific engagement described in this Agreement. Client is not obliged to offer further work to Consultant, and Consultant is not obliged to accept any work offered. This Agreement does not create a \"global\" or \"umbrella\" contract of employment or worker engagement.\n\n3.7 Control. Client controls only the outcome of the Services, not the manner in which they are performed. Consultant determines:\n(a) When and where to perform the Services (subject to reasonable Client requirements for meetings or site access);\n(b) The order and priority of tasks within the Services;\n(c) The tools, equipment, and methods used to perform the Services.\n\n3.8 Consultant''s Business. Consultant is responsible for providing tools, equipment, and materials necessary to perform the Services, maintaining any required business registrations (including with Companies House and HMRC), professional indemnity insurance, and operating Consultant''s business in compliance with applicable law. Consultant bears the financial risk of the engagement.\n\n3.9 Non-Exclusivity. Unless otherwise stated, Consultant may perform services for others during the Term, provided such services do not materially interfere with Consultant''s performance or breach this Agreement. Consultant confirms that Consultant provides similar services to other clients and markets services to the public generally.","type":"standard","order":3},{"id":"term_termination","title":"4. TERM; TERMINATION","content":"4.1 Term. This Agreement begins on the Effective Date and continues until {{expiration_date}}, unless earlier terminated in accordance with this Section (the \"Term\"). If no expiration date is specified, the Term shall continue until completion of the Services or termination as provided herein.\n\n4.2 Termination for Convenience. Either Party may terminate this Agreement for any reason upon written notice at least {{notice_period}} days prior to the effective termination date.\n\n4.3 Termination for Cause. Either Party may terminate immediately upon written notice if the other Party: (a) materially breaches this Agreement and fails to remedy such breach within 14 days after receiving written notice; (b) becomes insolvent or enters into administration, liquidation, or similar proceedings; or (c) engages in fraud or gross misconduct.\n\n4.4 Effect of Termination. Upon termination: (a) Consultant shall stop work except as necessary to wind down; (b) Consultant shall deliver to Client all Client property and Work Product created through the termination date; and (c) Client shall pay Consultant for Services properly performed through the termination date.\n\n4.5 Survival. Sections intended to survive shall survive termination, including Sections 5 (Intellectual Property), 6 (Confidentiality; Data Protection), 7 (Warranties), and 8 (Liability).","type":"standard","order":4},{"id":"intellectual_property","title":"5. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY; WORK PRODUCT","content":"5.1 Definitions. \"Work Product\" means all deliverables, work product, inventions, discoveries, developments, designs, works of authorship, documentation, reports, software, and other materials created by Consultant in connection with the Services.\n\n5.2 Ownership; Assignment. Client shall own all right, title, and interest in the Work Product. Consultant hereby assigns (and agrees to assign) to Client all rights in the Work Product, including all intellectual property rights, to the fullest extent permitted by law.\n\n5.3 Further Assurance. Consultant shall execute such documents and take such actions as Client may reasonably request to perfect Client''s rights in the Work Product.\n\n5.4 Consultant Background IP. \"Background IP\" means intellectual property owned or developed by Consultant outside the scope of this Agreement and not created specifically for Client. Consultant retains all rights in Background IP. To the extent Consultant incorporates Background IP into the Work Product, Consultant grants Client a perpetual, irrevocable, worldwide, royalty-free, transferable, and sublicensable licence to use such Background IP as part of the Work Product.\n\n5.5 Moral Rights. To the extent permitted by law, Consultant waives any moral rights in the Work Product under the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988 and agrees not to assert any such rights.\n\n5.6 No Restriction on Lawful Activities. Nothing in this Agreement prevents Consultant from engaging in any lawful profession or business, subject to confidentiality and non-solicitation obligations contained herein.","type":"negotiable","order":5},{"id":"confidentiality_data_protection","title":"6. CONFIDENTIALITY; UK GDPR; DATA PROTECTION","content":"6.1 Confidential Information. \"Confidential Information\" means any non-public information disclosed by Client to Consultant that is designated as confidential or that reasonably should be understood to be confidential. This includes business, financial, customer, technical, and trade secret information.\n\n6.2 Confidentiality Obligations. Consultant shall: (a) use Confidential Information solely to perform the Services; (b) protect Confidential Information using reasonable care; (c) not disclose Confidential Information except to personnel or permitted substitutes bound by confidentiality obligations; and (d) promptly notify Client of any suspected unauthorised disclosure.\n\n6.3 Exclusions. Confidential Information excludes information that: (a) is publicly available through no fault of Consultant; (b) was known to Consultant before disclosure; (c) is received from a third party without confidentiality restrictions; or (d) is independently developed without use of Confidential Information.\n\n6.4 Return/Destruction. Upon request or termination, Consultant shall return or destroy all Confidential Information, except for copies required for legal or regulatory compliance.\n\n6.5 UK GDPR Compliance. To the extent Consultant processes Personal Data (as defined in the UK General Data Protection Regulation (UK GDPR) and the Data Protection Act 2018) on behalf of Client in performing the Services:\n(a) Consultant shall process such data only on Client''s documented instructions and for the purposes of performing the Services;\n(b) Consultant shall implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure a level of security appropriate to the risk, including as appropriate: pseudonymisation and encryption, ensuring confidentiality, integrity, availability, and resilience, ability to restore access following an incident, and regular testing of security measures;\n(c) Consultant shall not engage a sub-processor without Client''s prior written consent;\n(d) Consultant shall not transfer Personal Data outside the United Kingdom unless: (i) there is an adequacy decision; (ii) appropriate safeguards are in place (such as Standard Contractual Clauses or binding corporate rules); or (iii) a derogation applies;\n(e) Consultant shall assist Client in responding to data subject requests and in meeting Client''s compliance obligations under Articles 32-36 of the UK GDPR;\n(f) Consultant shall notify Client without undue delay upon becoming aware of a Personal Data breach;\n(g) Upon termination, Consultant shall delete or return all Personal Data and certify such deletion unless retention is required by law;\n(h) Consultant shall make available information necessary to demonstrate compliance and allow for audits.\n\n6.6 Data Processing Agreement. If required, the Parties shall enter into a separate Data Processing Agreement incorporating the requirements of Article 28 of the UK GDPR.","type":"standard","order":6},{"id":"warranties","title":"7. WARRANTIES","content":"7.1 Mutual Authority. Each Party represents that it has authority to enter into this Agreement and that the person signing has been duly authorised.\n\n7.2 Consultant Warranties. Consultant represents and warrants that: (a) Consultant has the skill, experience, and resources to perform the Services; (b) the Services will be performed with reasonable skill and care; (c) Consultant will comply with all applicable laws; (d) the Work Product will not infringe third-party intellectual property rights to Consultant''s knowledge; (e) Consultant will not introduce malicious code into Client''s systems; and (f) Consultant has proper status as an independent contractor and is responsible for Consultant''s own tax affairs.\n\n7.3 Disclaimer. Except as expressly stated, neither Party makes any other warranties, including implied warranties of merchantability or fitness for a particular purpose, to the maximum extent permitted by law.","type":"standard","order":7},{"id":"liability","title":"8. LIABILITY; INSURANCE","content":"8.1 Consultant Liability. Consultant shall be liable for losses arising from Consultant''s breach of this Agreement, negligence, or wilful misconduct, subject to the limitations below.\n\n8.2 Limitation of Liability. Subject to Section 8.3:\n(a) Neither Party shall be liable for any indirect, consequential, or special damages (including lost profits, loss of business, or loss of goodwill) arising from this Agreement;\n(b) The total aggregate liability of either Party under or in connection with this Agreement (whether in contract, tort including negligence, breach of statutory duty, or otherwise) shall not exceed the greater of: (i) the total fees paid or payable under this Agreement in the 12 months preceding the claim; or (ii) GBP {{liability_cap}}.\n\n8.3 Unlimited Liability. Nothing in this Agreement limits or excludes liability for:\n(a) Death or personal injury caused by negligence;\n(b) Fraud or fraudulent misrepresentation;\n(c) Any liability which cannot be limited or excluded by law;\n(d) Wilful breach of confidentiality obligations; or\n(e) Infringement of intellectual property rights.\n\n8.4 Professional Indemnity Insurance. Consultant shall maintain professional indemnity insurance of at least GBP {{pi_insurance_amount}} per claim (or such higher amount as specified in {{services_description}}) throughout the Term and for 6 years thereafter.\n\n8.5 Public Liability Insurance. If Consultant is required to attend Client''s premises, Consultant shall maintain public liability insurance of at least GBP 1,000,000.\n\n8.6 Proof of Insurance. Upon Client''s request, Consultant shall provide certificates of insurance evidencing the required coverage.","type":"negotiable","order":8},{"id":"governing_law","title":"9. GOVERNING LAW; JURISDICTION","content":"9.1 Governing Law. This Agreement and any dispute or claim arising out of or in connection with it (including non-contractual disputes or claims) shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the law of England and Wales.\n\n9.2 Jurisdiction. The courts of England and Wales shall have exclusive jurisdiction to settle any dispute or claim arising out of or in connection with this Agreement, except that either Party may seek interim injunctive relief in any court of competent jurisdiction.","type":"standard","order":9},{"id":"general_provisions","title":"10. GENERAL PROVISIONS","content":"10.1 Notices. Notices must be in writing and delivered personally, by courier, by Royal Mail signed-for delivery, or by email with read receipt or confirmation of delivery.\n\n10.2 Assignment. Consultant may not assign or transfer this Agreement without Client''s prior written consent. Client may assign this Agreement in connection with a merger, acquisition, or sale of substantially all assets.\n\n10.3 Subcontracting. Subject to Section 3.5 (Right of Substitution), Consultant may not subcontract the Services without Client''s prior written consent. Consultant remains responsible for any subcontractors and substitutes.\n\n10.4 Relationship. The Parties are independent contractors. Nothing in this Agreement creates a partnership, joint venture, agency, or employment relationship.\n\n10.5 Compliance with Laws. Each Party shall comply with all applicable laws, including the Bribery Act 2010, the Modern Slavery Act 2015, and any applicable anti-money laundering legislation.\n\n10.6 Anti-Bribery. Each Party shall not engage in any activity that would constitute a bribery offence under the Bribery Act 2010, shall have adequate procedures to prevent bribery, and shall promptly report any suspected breach.\n\n10.7 Modern Slavery. Consultant represents that neither Consultant nor any of Consultant''s supply chain engages in any form of modern slavery or human trafficking.\n\n10.8 Severability. If any provision is held invalid or unenforceable, the remaining provisions shall remain in full force and effect, and the invalid provision shall be modified to the minimum extent necessary to make it valid and enforceable.\n\n10.9 Waiver. No waiver of any breach shall constitute a waiver of any prior or subsequent breach. Any waiver must be in writing.\n\n10.10 Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties regarding its subject matter and supersedes all prior negotiations, representations, and agreements. Each Party acknowledges that it has not relied on any representation not expressly set out herein.\n\n10.11 Amendments. Any amendment or modification must be in writing and signed by both Parties.\n\n10.12 Counterparts; Electronic Signatures. This Agreement may be executed in counterparts. Signatures delivered electronically are legally binding under the Electronic Communications Act 2000 and applicable common law principles.\n\n10.13 Third Party Rights. No person other than a Party to this Agreement shall have any rights under the Contracts (Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999 to enforce any term of this Agreement.\n\n10.14 Force Majeure. Neither Party shall be liable for any failure or delay in performing obligations due to circumstances beyond its reasonable control, provided that the affected Party notifies the other Party promptly and uses reasonable efforts to mitigate the effects.","type":"standard","order":10}]'::jsonb,
  'IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have executed this Agreement as of {{signature_date}}.

